{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Learn essential sound and haptic design principles and concepts for creating meaningful and delightful experiences that engage a wider range of human senses. Discover how to combine audio and haptics, using the Taptic Engine, to add a new level of realism and improve feedback in your app or game."}],"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"patch":0,"major":0},"metadata":{"title":"Designing Audio-Haptic Experiences","modules":[{"name":"WWDC Notes"}],"roleHeading":"WWDC19","role":"sampleCode"},"sections":[],"kind":"article","sampleCodeDownload":{"kind":"sampleDownload","action":{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"Watch Video (26 min)","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/wwdc19\/810"}},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"What-is-an-Audio-Haptic-Experience","type":"heading","text":"What is an Audio Haptic Experience?","level":2},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Some tones are so low that our ears cannot hear, however real speakers still produce a vibration that our body is still able to catch."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"One of the reasons behind the iPhone Taptic Engine is to reproduce those low frequency sounds\/vibrations."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The Taptic Engine works in sync with the iPhone speaker, resulting in an Audio Haptic Experience."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Three-Guiding-Principles","type":"heading","text":"Three Guiding Principles","level":2},{"anchor":"Causality","type":"heading","text":"Causality","level":3},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For feedback to be useful, it must be obvious what it caused it."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"For example a soccer hitting a ball:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"cause: foot colliding with the ball."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"effect: sound of impact, feel of impact"}]}]}],"type":"unorderedList"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"When designing sound\/haptics for your experience, think about what it’d feel\/sound like if what we interact with was a physical object.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Harmony","type":"heading","text":"Harmony","level":3},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Things should feel the way they look the way they sound.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Utility","type":"heading","text":"Utility","level":3},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Add audio and haptics that provide clear value to your app experience.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Written-By","type":"heading","text":"Written By","level":2},{"columns":[{"size":1,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"image","identifier":"zntfdr"}]}]},{"size":4,"content":[{"type":"heading","text":"zntfdr","anchor":"zntfdr","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/zntfdr","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Contributed Notes"}],"isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"Contributed Notes","type":"reference"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"|","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/zntfdr","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"|","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/","isActive":true,"type":"reference"}]}]}],"numberOfColumns":5,"type":"row"},{"type":"thematicBreak"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Missing anything? Corrections? ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/wwdcnotes.com\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/contributing","type":"reference","isActive":true}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Related-Sessions","type":"heading","text":"Related Sessions","level":2},{"items":["doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC19-223-Expanding-the-Sensory-Experience-with-Cor